C O R P O R A T E P A R T I C I P A N T S
Jared Isaacman Shift4 Payments, LLC - Founder & CEO
Taylor Lauber Shift4 Payments, LLC - Chief Strategy Officer
C O N F E R E N C E C A L L P A R T I C I P A N T S
Will Nance Goldman Sachs - Analyst
P R E S E N T A T I O N
Operator
Good day and thank you for standing by, and welcome to the Shift4 TMT Conference Call. (Operator Instructions) Please be
advised that today's conference is being recorded. (Operator Instructions)
I would now like to hand the conference over to your speaker today, Will Nance. Please go ahead.
Will Nance
Hey. Good afternoon, everyone, and thanks for joining us. My name is Will Nance. I cover the payments processes and IT
services space at Goldman Sachs. And I'm very happy to have with us the management team of Shift4. We've got Jared
Isaacman, who is the Founder and CEO; and Taylor Lauber, the Chief Strategy Officer.
So Jared, Taylor, I really appreciate you guys making the time. I think it's a super exciting story. There's a lot of interest in
the payments industry from investors these days and I think it's really exciting together to tell the story.
Maybe we could start off with something that most of the folks in the audience may be able to relate to after the
last year, and it had seemed like everybody is moving out on to the suburbs. I was hoping maybe you could talk a
little bit about what you're seeing across your merchant base now. Maybe how that compares to the depths of the
downturn back in April?
Jared Isaacman
Sure. Hey, Will. And good afternoon, everyone. Pleasure to be here. As Will mentioned, I'm Jared Isaacman. I'm the Founder
and CEO of Shift4 Payments. And I'll just kick it off by saying that the recovery is certainly well underway, although just like
the pandemic itself, not evenly distributed at all. We're seeing a pretty meaningful acceleration towards normal really since
Labor Day across our various customer segments.
If you just carve up some of the big pieces of the portfolio, our restaurant merchants now are in total at about 90%
of 2019 levels, where we're indexed to quick service and fast casual. So that's been pretty stable throughout and
more of the table [crap] (sic) [tablecloth] restaurants are the ones that are driving that recovery.
Hotels, we're seeing a pretty big acceleration. It's around 70% of 2019 levels. And as a reminder, our hotel mix
is largely domestic, a little bit of Caribbean, not a lot of international travel. And it's less kind of business travel
and more leisure travel. So you're seeing those weekend occupancy rates really kind of get back to close to normal,
although the average daily rate is still down pretty considerably. So that's driving that number.
And then our other specialty vertical markets like entertainment and leisure are also recovering pretty nicely,
indexed almost entirely towards kind of regional type establishments. So theme parks, ski mountains, minor league
sports, that's contributing to the stabilization we're seeing in the recovery.
